Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A lunatic asylum where young people are supposed to meet today.
A crypt chapel, where digging is now underway for the S-Bahn tunnel.
Allotment gardeners cultivate what was once farmers' land.
The oldest official map of Munich brings exciting stories to light.
It's annoying when maps are not up to date.
Everyone who has ever had to get upset because the car navigation system showed a green meadow instead of a bypass knows this.
The historical maps of the digital Bavarian Atlas, a service of the Bavarian Geoportal of the state government, are anything but up-to-date - but that is precisely why they are very informative.
Especially if you compare them with current online maps.
Then it becomes clear how towns and communities in the circulation area of the Münchner Merkur have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bavarian Atlas is a patchwork quilt that is not immediately recognisable as such.
More detailed maps, so-called original position sheets, were incorporated into the large general map for towns and municipalities.
According to the Bavarian Survey Administration, these were created between 1810 and 1864 and originate from the first survey of Bavaria.
Their client: Napoleon.
The French army commander had occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied land and commissioned a topographical survey of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Even though the French troops finally withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville on 9 February 1801: it was today's neighbours who created the idea of an area-wide map of Bavaria.
Elector Max IV Joseph pushed the project further, founded the "Topographical Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The original position sheet for Munich dates from 1856 and can be found, like all others, on the website of the Bavarian State Library.
The comparison of past and present is most impressive when looking at the example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which still appears relatively isolated on the 1856 map.
Sendling was incorporated as a Munich district 21 years after the map was drawn up, in 1877.
Today Untersendling lies in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendling were concentrated around 1856 along what is now Plinganserstrasse, which was not named after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the Bavarian peasants' uprising against Austria in 1705, until 1878.
Where the Westpark is today, you see nothing but fields - at first glance: Zooming in, a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers appears: handwritten numbered parcels from the so-called "primitive survey" from which the land tax was derived.
Small plots of land are no longer occupied by farmers - but by allotment gardeners of the "Land in Sonne" site.
A large green area is emerging to the north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, the venue of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was indeed still a meadow in the 19th century - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the original location sheet, one reads in the area of today's district of Au-Haidhausen not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the hill "Auf der Lüften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, people with delusions were once locked up here on Auerfeldstraße.
The Munich district insane asylum "Auf der Auer Lüften" was established there in 1858/59.
From 1872, the institution was run by Dr. Bernhard von Gudden - the psychiatrist who is associated with the death of King Ludwig II.
"He was progressive for his time and ended, for example, the chaining of the so-called lunatics.
He also forbade the staff from using violence against the inmates," says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Haidhausen Museum, who has studied the asylum for an exhibition.
Initially, there was room for 280 patients, but later it was expanded to 500 places.
At some point, even this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for building the Kreisirrenanstalt in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany, has been located there.
On the site of the former Auer asylum, young people now meet in the Munich Salesianum.
The order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training facilities.
To the west is the football pitch of TSV München Ost, to the east residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the Casa Don Bosco children's home was built - architecturally based on the original building of the asylum, which was destroyed in bombing raids during the Second World War.
Around 1856, Marienplatz was listed as "Haupt Platz", Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change to the heart of Munich.
The Allied bombs tore many holes in the city centre in December 1944.
A large one remained to this day - at Marienhof.
The English Institute, small commercial buildings and a crypt chapel from the Middle Ages once stood at Marienhof, where preliminary work is taking place these days and the groundbreaking ceremony for the second S-Bahn main line will take place on 5 April 2017.
