Pasture fence project is elementary
The Fischerbach pasture fence project is a success and will be continued in the coming year.
The CDU members of parliament Peter Weiß and Kordula Kovac went to see for themselves.
Representatives of the Fischerbach CDU local association met with Mayor Thomas Schneider and the two MPs at the Schwendemann family's Rechtgrabenhof farm.
Markus Schwendemann first provided insights into his farm, where he manages 55 hectares of meadows and 40 hectares of forest, looks after 40 dairy cows and just as many young animals, and accommodates holiday guests in five flats.
According to Schwendemann, "Schwarzwaldmilch" is the marketing channel for his cows' milk that has no alternative.
Only regional products are served to the holiday guests.
As he is also BLHV chairman of Fischerbach, he described the pasture fence project as "elementarily important".
I cannot farm profitably on such steep land.
The grassland makes for a lot of work, he said, and much of it has to be worked with a brush scythe.
"We have to struggle with the conditions and the topography here," Schwendemann emphasised.
He took over his parents' farm in 2003 and manages it without chemical pesticides and fertilisers, even though he does not run an organic farm.
For Mayor Thomas Schneider it was clear: "The municipality has recognised the importance of the pasture fence project and is happy about the Leader funding".
With costs of 3000 to 4000 euros per hectare, the farmers needed to be supported.
It is hoped that this could drag out the afforestation of the land for quite a while.
"The greatest treasure we have is the people who work in agriculture and think about how to take their farm further," the mayor stressed.
Farmers are often criticised over subsidies
A total of 25 plots were fenced in 2013 by eleven participants through the pasture fence subsidy.
The area kept open thus amounts to 40 hectares, which may not be afforested until at least 2023.
Of the total costs of 71,500 euros, half was funded by Leader and one quarter was borne by the municipality of Fischerbach.
This left the farmers with 12,610 euros to invest in 16.2 kilometres of pasture fence.
"The big advantage is the longevity of the fences," Schwendemann explained.
Kordula Kovac emphasised: "You are doing a really good job, you can't do it without farmers and countrywomen".
For Peter Weiß, too, it was clear: "The best food is produced here".
The Landscape Maintenance Directive (LPR) of Baden-Württemberg allows for state funding of pasture fences.
The aim is to keep the Black Forest open.
The prerequisite is the existence of a subsidised area designated by the LPR.
In addition, the area to be fenced in must not be cultivable by tractors (slope inclination over 35 percent) and must therefore be threatened by afforestation.
For the Fischerbach pasture fence project 2018, the application of eight participants with 24 plots is currently underway, who would like to build almost 16 kilometres of fence.
The area to be kept open corresponds to 35 hectares, and the calculated costs are more than 112,000 euros.
