No Davis Cup reform: Best-of-five continues
The President of the International Tennis Federation (ITF) failed with his big Davis Cup coup at the General Assembly.
At the meeting in Ho Chi Minh City, the proposal to play Davis Cup singles in only two winning sets, which is revolutionary for this sport, was not supported by the required two-thirds majority by a razor-thin margin.
The five-set classics, which are often very long but therefore also very much appreciated, will therefore remain in the traditional competition.
63.54 per cent of member countries voted in favour of the reform, so ITF President David Haggerty's target was only narrowly missed.
"We respect this decision but are disappointed that our member nations did not approve the full reform package for the Davis Cup and Fed Cup.
We need change to secure the long-term future of these iconic and historic competitions," Haggerty said.
They will continue to work to improve the competitions, he added.
The proposal to hold the final at a neutral venue was not even put to the vote after many objections.
Only comparatively minor details are new from 2018: for example, the finalists in the Davis Cup and Fed Cup will have the right to host the first round in the following year.
In order to reduce the costs for the organisers, the requirements in terms of training grounds etc. will be eased and the players will have to attend fewer official media appointments before the Davis Cup.
Elon Musk doesn't care: Tens of thousands of Tesla customers cancel orders
Electric thausendassa Elon Musk likes to brag about the huge number of pre-orders for his new Tesla "Model 3".
Yet he has so far failed to mention that some of the customers have already cancelled their non-binding reservations.
In addition to the always triumphant figures on sales increases and even more gigantic sales targets, Tesla boss Elon Musk revealed another, less glamorous figure for the first time when announcing the latest quarterly financial statement: that of cancellations for the new mass-market Model 3.
In recent months, Musk had frequently advertised the more than 500,000 pre-orders for the new car, which is just starting to be delivered.
Now Musk admits: Of the total 518,000 pre-orders, 63,000 have already been withdrawn.
Critics had repeatedly pointed out that these were only non-binding reservations.
In the event of a cancellation, Tesla will refund the 1000 euro (in the USA 1000 US dollars and in Great Britain 1000 pounds) "reservation deposit" in full.
Musk admitted in a conference call with analysts that there were currently 455,000 such non-binding reservations.
However, the Tesla boss does not believe that the cancellation of around twelve percent of all orders to date could become a problem.
His argument: the challenge with the ambitious growth targets does not lie with demand, but on the production side.
Last year, Tesla delivered 84,000 vehicles.
In 2018 - all models taken together - it should be 500,000, and in 2020 one million.
The demand is obviously there.
According to Musk, 1800 reservations are currently being added every day.
Anyone who orders a Model 3 today can expect delivery in the second half of 2018 at the earliest - if Tesla manages to run its brand-new production lines, which have never been tested in practice, at maximum capacity without major interruptions.
Many experts doubt that this is possible.
But if there are major delays, the non-binding nature of the reservations could become a problem for Tesla.
Because then the company cannot prevent dissatisfied customers from running away in droves.
Tumlingen celebrates 750 years of St. Hilarius Church
750 years of St. Hilarius Church: On the occasion of the mountain church's anniversary, an invitation is extended to a serenade on the old cemetery grounds in Tumlingen on Sunday, 16 July, at 4.30 pm.
Due to its idyllic location and beautiful view of the village, the historic St. Hilarius grounds are a popular place to linger.
Visitors to the sixth benefit serenade can let themselves be enchanted by this powerful place.
The friends and supporters of Tumlingen have made the rescue and preservation of the oldest building in the village their concern.
Walter Martini emphasises: "It is a unique village gem".
In 1267, the St. Hilarius Chapel was first mentioned in a document in the Württemberg Book of Documents: Count Hermann von Sulz sold "the hill with the parish church of Tumlingen on it, together with the bailiwick" to Magister Eberhard von Horb and his brother Dietrich for 20 marks of silver.
According to the wording of the deed, in addition to the former parish church, there was also a manorial farm on the Tumlingen hill, to which the church or the patronage right belonged and not vice versa.
So people also lived there.
As can be seen from the description of the Oberamt Freudenstadt from 1858, the "Berg" was the third, manorial settlement core of the village, in addition to the Unterdorf and the Oberdorf, which can just be recognised today in the townscape of Tumlingen.
Old maps from around 1600 support these historical facts.
The right of patronage developed from the early medieval right to own a church.
A lord who built a church, equipped it and staffed it with a priest remained the owner of this church and could also bequeath it.
This was connected with the right to appoint a pastor or to propose a new pastor to the bishop.
There were three altars in the church and two bells on the tower.
The larger of the two burst at Christmas 1673.
The newly acquired bell then rang out for the first time in 1692, but later had to be surrendered during the Second World War in 1942.
During the 30 Years' War (1616 to 1648), the window panes were smashed and the bell ropes stolen.
The roof was leaking.
In 1796, French troops camped near the church.
They broke out the pulpit and pews and used them as firewood.
Remains of the church threatened to collapse in 1809.
Until 1869, the Tumlingen Hilarius cemetery also served as the final resting place for the dead from Hörschweiler.
In 1823, the cemetery was extended and the Hilarius Church was demolished.
Only the church tower was left standing.
On New Year's Eve 1834, a storm split the church tower in two and half of it collapsed.
To prevent a disaster, the tower was demolished.
Only the tower dwarf, which still exists today, was preserved as a witness to 750 years of church history.
Today, Horst Kallenberger and Rolf-Dieter Wasem of the "Schaffige Rentnern" (retired people) take care of the Hilarius grounds as Dieter Dockhorn's successors.
As organisers, the Friends and Supporters of Tumlingen invite you to the sixth Serenade on Sunday, 16 July, in the old cemetery at the St. Hilarius Chapel.
It will be performed by the combo of the Kepler Grammar School in Freudenstadt and will feature speeches by Kurt Kübler and Reinhold Matteis.
Hartmut Romann, head of the village, will give the closing address.
The programme begins at 4.30 pm.
Admission is from 3.30 pm.
At the end of the serenade, there will be a drink in front of the cemetery.
"Enjoy a summer evening under the shade of old trees and with the wide view over meadows to the forest", the organisers emphasise the fantastic view.
The serenade will only take place in dry weather.
The organisers hope for many supporters for the preservation of the historic St. Hilarius site, which is important for Tumlingen and Hörschweiler.
The Friends and Supporters of Tumlingen feel particularly committed to the preservation of local history, as serenade organiser Walter Martini affirms.
Association wants to have approval for wind turbines examined
"Boisheim wehrt sich" (Boisheim defends itself) sees no legal prerequisite for the construction and has therefore turned to the district administrator.
The association "Boisheim wehrt sich" (Boisheim defends itself) has called on District Administrator Andreas Coenen (CDU) to withdraw his approval for the construction of planned wind turbines in the Boisheimer Nette.
It was granted unlawfully.
The association argues that at the time of the approval on 30 December 2016, no wind turbines could have been approved in the Boisheimer Nette, as at that time there was only a wind power concentration zone in Viersen on the city border with Schwalmtal.
Within this concentration zone, the construction and operation of wind turbines is possible in principle, but at the same time the concentration zone has the effect of excluding the use of wind energy for the rest of the town.
Such zones are intended to prevent the landscape from being "covered in vegetation".
A few days earlier, the town of Viersen had decided on a second wind power concentration zone in the Boisheimer Nette by amending the land use plan - but the district government of Düsseldorf had not approved it because of a formal error.
"Due to the missing planning law requirement, the notice of approval issued is still illegal and therefore also to be withdrawn," said Christoph Erkens, chairman of "Boisheim wehrt sich" (Boisheim defends itself).
The current state of affairs: Before the summer break, the town council again approved the wind concentration zone in the Boisheim Nette; approval from the district government is still pending.
Erkens: "This rules out the granting of a permit for the erection of wind turbines at this location under planning law".
The district confirms receipt of the request.
"The corresponding letters have been received by the district of Viersen since last week," a spokesperson explained.
The district is taking them as an opportunity to re-examine the matter.
However, they will probably not lead to the procedure being stopped.
In view of the ongoing proceedings at the administrative court, the district did not want to comment on the content of the argumentation of the association "Boisheim wehrt sich" on Thursday.
NEW Re, a subsidiary of NEW, plans to build four wind turbines, each 200 metres high, on a site on the Boisheimer Nette.
Last year, the company, in which the town of Viersen holds an indirect stake, had already concluded lease agreements with the owner of the 65-hectare site.
With the erection of the four wind turbines, it should be possible to cover the electricity needs of about 11,400 households - which corresponds to about one fifth of the electricity needs of all households in Viersen.
NEW Re plans to invest around 20 million euros.
Last summer, Viersen's city council gave the green light for the purchase of three wind turbines in the Linnich wind farm near Aachen as well as an investment in a wind turbine in Übach-Palenberg in the Heinsberg district.
