Max Menge works as a volunteer
You work in several places during your volunteer year.
Where everywhere?
Menge: Usually in Steinfurt at the furniture exchange, once a week I help out here in Greven at the Möbelbrücke.
And I have already worked in the open all-day at the school.
What are your experiences with this?
Menge: It's a nice, broad spectrum that I see here.
I deal with different people, with young people, with refugees, with young adults.
You are now 26 years old, so you are a late-career volunteer.
How come?
Menge: I graduated from high school.
And then, let's say, successfully dropped out of a civil engineering course.
I realised that it was wrong for me and that I wanted to do something else, work with people.
And then I asked myself, what are you doing?
Do a social year, you get an insight, you can see what it's really like on the ground, maybe in a hot spot.
And was it like that?
Menge: I gained some great impressions.
I will start my studies in social work in the winter semester.
I will study dual, probably do social work training at the Youth Welfare Office in Herne and study at the University of Applied Sciences in Hamm.
Isn't it a bit unusual to have several different places of work during your voluntary service?
Menge: Yes, it is very variable.
I guess it always depends on where you do your FSJ.
You can do it in anything from an old people's home to youth work - in all possible facets of social work.
For me, it was very varied.
I was also partly in the OGS, that is, in the afternoon care.
For me, that was exactly what appealed to me.
I was able to recognise my own strengths and see how things really work.
Is it different from studying civil engineering?
Menge: Of course, here it's not about calculating statics.
You always have other people in front of your head, each of whom has a completely different story behind them.
Whether it's a refugee or a young person who has been taken away from their family - you always have to deal with them individually.
Very interesting.
And you had no fear of contact?
Menge: I'm not the type for that.
It's an area that gives you a lot.
A lot of love, a lot of kindness.
There are also negative moments, but that's life.
