The members want to set up boards along the planned route and provide information about stars and constellations.
In a first phase until 2018, the association is planning "easily accessible installations at five to six locations" in the Upper Harz.
St. Andreasberg, Braunlage, Hohegeiß and Sieber are possible candidates.
The information on the boards is to be supplemented via the internet.
Therefore, good mobile network reception plays a role in the selection of locations.
Accessibility is also a criterion.
Later, the star trail will be expanded step by step.
"On the star trail, the viewers learn a lot of interesting facts, for example about the physics of the individual stars," the association explained.
They also learn why stars have different colours or why one star shines more brightly than another even though it is much further away.
They also learn in which constellation a selected star is located and when it is best visible.
The association has been operating the highest observatory in northern Germany in the mountain town of St. Andreasberg since 2014.
According to the Federal Agency for Nature Conservation, the location in the middle of the Harz National Park is one of the six darkest regions in Germany.
Often the Milky Way and even the Andromeda Galaxy can be seen clearly with the naked eye from there.
In the university town, there has been something similar to the planned star dwarf in place since 2003 on the initiative of the Planetarium Friends Association - the Planet Trail.
Starting in front of Gebhard's Hotel in Goetheallee, which forms the interior of our solar system, the Planetary Path with its steles leads up to the Hainberg and the observatory - as well as an "extraterrestrial" location in Diemarden (Gleichen municipality) with the planet Sedna.
The steles with the individual planets - including Pluto, which has been demoted to a dwarf planet at the end point - are set up exactly at a distance and scale of one to two billion.
The Earth thus shrinks to a sphere 6.5 millimetres in diameter, while the Sun, standing exactly 75 metres away, measures 70 centimetres.
The total distance of the planetary path is a good four kilometres.
While it takes light about eight hours to reach Pluto from the sun, it takes pedestrians a good hour to reach the stele with Pluto.
So pedestrians are faster than light in space.
But the march to the nearest fixed star would still take half a year.
