Interview with the Minister of Agriculture - How do we protect ourselves from poisonous eggs, Mr Schmidt?
Germany is discussing contaminated eggs.
How could the scandal happen?
How can consumers protect themselves.
Agriculture Minister Christian Schmidt (CSU) answers questions in an interview with RedaktionsNetzwerk Deutschland (RND).
Mr Schmidt, how can consumers protect themselves from poisoned eggs?
I can only encourage all consumers to take a close look at the eggs in your fridge and check the stamp.
On the consumer protection portal www.Lebensmittelwarnung.de, the federal states post the latest information on the affected egg batches.
Affected eggs should be destroyed or returned.
Even if, according to all we know at present, a health risk is practically excluded.
Is Aldi now taking over the best possible crisis response - all eggs out of the range - because the central role of clarifying the situation is not really being performed by the Federal Minister of Agriculture?
Food monitoring is the task of the federal states.
Nevertheless, my office immediately stepped in and has been in close contact with the authorities of the federal states ever since Germany became aware of the problem.
All information and the risk assessment are available to consumers.
The trade, just like the manufacturers, has to ensure that the products sold are marketable and harmless to health.
If the maximum residue level of 0.005mg/kg is exceeded in eggs, they are not marketable.
However, uncontaminated eggs can be sold and consumed.
This time it is not the farms that are to blame.
Are production companies and consumers in the same boat?
According to the current state of knowledge, the production companies are not directly to blame.
Rather, they have to expect economic damage due to alleged illegal practices by service companies.
As always, there are too few inspectors in case of emergency.
Is it just a lack of staff or is there also a lack of coherent responsibility?
After all, it was precisely the official controls that uncovered the case.
However, the truth is that food fraud and criminal energy can never be 100 per cent ruled out.
It is precisely for this reason that consistent investigation of such incidents and handing them over to the public prosecutor's offices in cases where criminal offences may have been committed are of crucial importance.
I have already made it clear on several occasions that I expect the responsible authorities to carry out a complete investigation.
Is the regular alarmism about food scandals really necessary?
Consumers have the right to receive only safe and marketable food.
When an unauthorised insecticide is used in the food industry, consumers are rightly outraged.
The adulterated product has put producers, traders and consumers in a situation that is absolutely unnecessary.
Basically, it must be clear: The illegal use of the insecticide fipronil in the keeping of food-producing animals is unacceptable and must be stopped immediately.
Work on this must be done consistently and at full speed at all levels.
I expect all responsible authorities to clarify the facts quickly and completely.
