Russia Affair: US Special Investigator Appoints Grand Jury
In the Russia affair surrounding US President Donald Trump, special investigator Robert Mueller is said to have appointed a so-called grand jury, according to a report.
The panel has begun work in recent weeks, wrote the Wall Street Journal, citing people familiar with the matter.
The newspaper interpreted the move as a sign that Mueller had expanded and intensified his investigation.
CNN reported that the first subpoenas had already been issued by the panel in connection with a meeting between Trump's eldest son and a Russian lawyer.
US intelligence agencies have long accused the Kremlin of deliberately interfering in the 2016 presidential election campaign.
Mueller is investigating whether there was collusion between Trump's campaign team and Moscow.
The investigation is said to focus on several men who acted as advisors to the Republican during the election campaign.
According to reports, Mueller also increasingly scrutinised Trump's private and business environment.
The Washington Post wrote a few weeks ago that the special prosecutor had put Trump personally at the centre and was investigating allegations that the president may have obstructed justice in the course of the affair.
The main task of grand juries is to examine available evidence in possible criminal cases and decide whether to bring charges.
Grand juries are therefore also called indictment chambers.
They are usually called in when there are major and controversial cases.
The proceedings are always conducted behind closed doors.
The panel can also be called in by the prosecution to subpoena people for questioning under oath.
According to CNN, subpoenas have already been issued concerning the meeting between Donald Trump Jr. and a Russian lawyer.
People involved in the meeting have been asked to testify, the report said.
They were also asked to provide documents.
In addition to Trump Jr, Trump's adviser and son-in-law Jared Kushner and his then campaign chairman Paul Manafort were also present at the meeting.
Legal experts said on US television on Thursday evening that the appointment showed that Mueller was not intimidated in his work and that he wanted to act quickly if necessary.
However, it does not necessarily mean that the grand jury will be called in at the end to decide whether to bring an indictment.
Nevertheless, the appointment of the panel is the beginning of a new phase in the investigation and a new cause for concern for President Trump.
Amid the new revelations, the president used a speech in West Virginia on Thursday night to portray the Russia affair as a campaign by his political opponents.
"The Russia story is a total fabrication," Trump said.
The issue, he said, gives Democrats a way to "feel good about themselves because they have nothing else to talk about."
His special adviser Ty Cobb said in a statement that he was not aware of a grand jury being set up.
But the grand jury usually works in secret, he stressed.
The White House is in favour of any measures that would speed up the work of the special investigator in a "fair" way.
Former FBI chief James Comey had said three times that the president was not under investigation.
There was no reason to believe that this had changed, the statement added.
However, Mueller was only appointed after Trump had fired Comey.
Because of this dismissal, accusations had been made against Trump that he had wanted to obstruct justice.
Comey testified before a Senate committee in June that Trump had asked him to drop the investigation into the then national security adviser Michael Flynn.
The president is under great pressure because of the investigation.
According to US media, the White House collected material against the special investigator and his staff.
This triggered speculation about whether Trump wanted to fire Mueller.
Unlike an independent special congressional investigator, such as in the Watergate affair involving President Richard Nixon, who later resigned, Mueller has a position in which he could theoretically be fired by the Justice Department at the president's insistence.
Several senators from both parties, however, want to forestall such a move.
Two groups of Republican and Democratic senators introduced bills on Thursday under which the special investigator could no longer be fired so easily.
Antarctica: Giant iceberg drifts in Antarctica
A gigantic iceberg almost seven times the size of Berlin has broken away from the ice shelf in West Antarctica.
This was announced by the Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research in Bremerhaven on Wednesday.
The colossus, which weighs over a trillion tonnes and covers 5800 square kilometres, is now drifting northwards and will probably take two or three years to melt.
At 175 kilometres long and up to 50 kilometres wide, it is one of the largest ice giants researchers have recorded in the past three decades.
It poses no danger to humans.
According to researchers, it is unclear to what extent climate change has played a role in the break-up of the iceberg.
Overall, however, there has been a series of unusual ice shelf collapses in the region for about 30 years, the US National Snow and Ice Research Centre (NSIDC) writes in a factual backgrounder.
According to many researchers, this could be related to global warming.
The now broken-off colossus was previously part of the Larsen C Ice Shelf.
Ice shelves float on the sea and are fed by large glaciers.
It thus grows further and further into the sea and regularly breaks off.
The Larsen C Ice Shelf lies south of South America almost at the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula.
North of this ice shelf, the balance of growing and breaking off was disturbed a few years ago.
A complete ice shelf had disintegrated there, writes AWI researcher Daniela Jansen.
There are indications that the Larsen C Ice Shelf is also in danger, because the leading edge has never retreated as far as it is now.
In addition, the ice plate is under tension and could disintegrate if a piece breaks off at a key point.
Melting ice shelves and icebergs do not raise sea levels because they float on water and ice displaces as much water as it yields after melting itself.
However, the loss of the ice shelf causes the glaciers to flow directly into the sea and drain much faster than before.
This could eventually raise sea levels, but only slightly, writes the British Antarctic Monitoring Research Project (Midas).
According to AWI, the Larsen C Ice Shelf is the fourth largest ice shelf in Antarctica, covering almost 50,000 square kilometres.
At the transition from the mainland it is up to 700 metres thick, at the leading edge to the open ocean around 200 metres.
There it breaks off regularly.
"Although it is a natural occurrence and we are not aware of any direct link to climate change, the ice sheet is now coming into a more vulnerable position," said Martin O'Leary of Swansea University in the UK.
"This is the furthest retreat since records began," he also acknowledged.
It is a matter of debate among scientists whether the Larsen C Ice Shelf will now grow again or decline in the long term and possibly collapse, said his colleague Adrian Luckman, adding, "Our models say it will be less stable."
But this development will take decades, he said.
Even if these researchers do not attribute the break-up of this gigantic iceberg to climate change, a great many ice shelves on the Antarctic Peninsula have disintegrated in recent decades.
This long tip of Antarctica stretches towards South America.
According to data from the British Antarctic Survey research programme, the ice surface of the Antarctic Peninsula has shrunk by 28,000 square kilometres since the 1950s.
The rise in temperature has contributed to the decline.
The Antarctic Peninsula has warmed by about three degrees in the past 50 years, making it one of the areas where temperatures are rising fastest.
