Consoles instead of grass - Bundesliga gears up for e-sports
Will the sports stars be sitting in front of computer consoles in future instead of sweating their way across the stadium turf in wind and weather?
The fact is that e-sports has long since become a serious industry, a lucrative business - including big stars, millions of fans and huge tournaments with high fees.
The first Bundesliga clubs have also recognised this and are becoming increasingly involved in this field.
VfL Wolfsburg made the start in 2015, followed later by FC Schalke 04 and most recently VfB Stuttgart, which founded an e-sports department in mid-July and signed two professionals for the computer game FIFA 17.
"We hope this will inspire completely new young target groups for VfB," says board member Jochen Röttgermann.
He is sure that "many more clubs will get on board this train".
This coming weekend, the world football association FIFA is organising the first "Interactive Club World Cup" in London, where gamers from different clubs will compete against each other.
In addition to Schalke and Wolfsburg, Manchester City, Paris Saint-Germain and PSV Eindhoven have also qualified.
Robin Dutt also sees great potential in e-sports.
The ex-coach of Bayer Leverkusen and Werder Bremen now advises an agency for virtual football players.
"Real football has to deal with the 14 to 30-year-olds in particular, that young people will still go to the stadium in the future," says the 52-year-old.
And: the clubs are trying to conquer all kinds of markets, especially the Asian ones.
With prominent e-sportsmen under contract, one could be present online on these markets far more often than just sending the Bundesliga team to Asia once a year.
What exactly is it about?
In e-sports, computer games like "League Of Legends", "Dota 2", "Counterstrike" or the football simulation FIFA are played on a competitive level.
As in normal sports, leagues have long since been established in which professionals compete against each other.
And e-sports are already part of the official programme for the 2022 Asian Games.
But is it a real sport at all?
For many, the idea certainly takes some getting used to.
Ingo Froböse has also grappled with the question for a long time.
For the professor at the German Sport University in Cologne, e-sport is a sport because it is competitive and shows many biological and physical reactions that are also found in classical sport - for example, increased heart rates, stress reactions, hormonal changes.
In addition, it requires cognitive abilities, a technical and tactical understanding and a quick reaction time.
Professional gamers should not only train at the console, but also train their body and pay attention to nutrition.
"The fit gamer is a good gamer."
Froböse also sees problems, however: "Doping is becoming more and more of an issue."
Controls are difficult to carry out in online games, he says, and the scene lacks the structures of classic sport.
On the positive side, the scientist emphasises the high integrative effect of e-sports.
The players travel internationally, it's like a big global family, there are no intercultural barriers.
A study by the consulting firm Deloitte and the Federal Association of Interactive Entertainment Software (BIU) predicts rapid growth for e-sports.
In 2016, 50 million euros were turned over with it in Germany, mainly through advertising, sponsoring and large tournaments.
In three years, the turnover is expected to be 130 million.
Compared to the almost 2.4 billion euros generated by the German Football League, this is not much.
However, e-sports are "no longer far removed from other established sports such as handball, basketball or ice hockey", write the Deloitte consultants.
Internationally, many countries are already further along.
Large markets are Asia and the USA, where ex-basketball player Shaquille O`Neal and baseball star Alex Rodriguez participate in the US team NRG eSports.
Hollywood actor Ashton Kutcher invests in the eSports betting provider Unikrn.
Things are also happening in Europe.
In a Norwegian school, e-sports has been introduced as a subject, says Froböse.
In the Netherlands and France, first-division football clubs are now obliged to set up an e-sports department, according to Dutt.
"Compared to other European countries, Germany is lagging behind," explains VfB board member Röttgermann.
Today, it is no longer enough to just fall into nostalgia and glorify the old days.
It is about preserving the tradition of the club, but at the same time aligning the company with the modern market.
"We live in a digitalised world," Dutt agrees.
"You can't cling to the idea that only in football everything stays the same as it always was."
