Deutsche Bahn: Group tests "comfort check-in
It is a moment that almost everyone has experienced: You are sitting in the train, unsuspecting, and asleep.
Or you are absorbed in your work and have just had a brilliant thought.
And then: poof.
The conductor comes and wakes you up rudely or pulls you out of the workflow.
Ticket check.
But the days of interruptions will soon be over.
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing conductorless ticket control.
You simply confirm by mobile phone that you have taken your seat and validate your ticket with it.
Test operations are currently underway on two routes.
"If the service is successful, we will expand it.
It will then probably be available on many more long-distance routes in Germany at the beginning of next year," said a Bahn spokesperson.
"Komfort Check-in" is what the railway calls the ticket validation without a conductor.
In order to be able to use it, however, a few requirements must be met: You need a smartphone or a tablet.
And you have to have booked an online ticket - which most passengers already do anyway.
You also need to have bought it via the DB Navigator app, which is the most convenient way to book tickets anyway.
And lastly, you need a seat reservation.
Because the "Comfort Check-in" works like this: you get on the train, call up your ticket under "My Tickets".
A button for electronic validation then appears for the test customers.
The train attendants receive a message on their mobile devices that passenger X is on the train and has taken the booked seat Y. If the train attendant checks in at the ticket office, the ticket is validated electronically.
If the train attendant comes to seat Y during the ticket check, he knows that a passenger with an already validated online ticket is sitting there.
So you can continue to sleep, continue to work, continue to be silent.
The "check-in" has two advantages: one for the customer, one for the railway - which in turn should benefit the passengers.
"Those who want to travel in a relaxed manner without ticket checks by our train attendants simply check in themselves in the DB Navigator.
This allows passengers to personalise their travel time on the train," says Michael Peterson, Marketing Director of DB Fernverkehr.
Second plus: "And our staff have more time than today to respond to individual customer needs".
