Military Reforms in Turkey - Erdogan's Fear of the Army
Every year at the beginning of August, the Supreme Military Council (YAS) in Ankara discusses retirements and promotions in the officer corps.
This week was no exception.
At first glance, a normal procedure.
But nothing is routine in the Turkish armed forces one year after the coup attempt.
The meeting was no longer held in the General Staff building, as in the past, but in the Prime Minister's official residence.
The five deputy prime ministers as well as the ministers of defence, interior, justice and foreign affairs now also took part in the deliberations under the chairmanship of the head of government.
This meant that the civilians were in the majority at the YAS.
The government is tightening the reins on the military.
Chief of General Staff Hulusi Akar remains in office, but the commanders of the army, air force and navy have been removed.
Since the failed coup, head of state Erdogan has fired 169 of the 326 generals and admirals.
Over 10,000 soldiers have been removed from the ranks of the army - mostly for alleged links to the movement of exiled preacher Fethullah Gülen, whom Erdogan sees as the mastermind of the coup attempt.
486 people who are alleged to have been directly involved in the coup attempt have been on trial in Ankara since this week.
The day after the coup, Erdogan had already described the attempted coup as a "godsend", as it gave him the opportunity to "completely cleanse" the armed forces.
But does Erdogan really have the army under control?
At the end of February, the newspaper "Hürriyet" published an article with the headline "Unease at Military Headquarters".
The newspaper wrote that there were concerns in the general staff about an increasing "Islamisation" of the army, which manifested itself, among other things, in the lifting of the headscarf ban for female soldiers.
In any case, the major clean-up of the army and the security forces continues.
In mid-July, Erdogan issued a decree firing another 7395 civil servants, including 2303 police officers and 546 soldiers.
It seemed as if Erdogan had tamed the military.
The generals used to be considered the real masters of the country.
Three times they putsched, citing their role as guardians of the secular order of the state.
After his election victory in 2002, Erdogan pushed back the power of the military step by step, not least by invoking the reform requirements of the European Union.
Former officers say Erdogan is deliberately pushing for an Islamisation of the armed forces.
In the magazine "Vocal Europe", an unnamed officer who sought asylum abroad after the coup attempt for fear of persecution warned that the Turkish army would be "full of extremists and Salafists" in a few years.
If that is true, such a development could not leave NATO cold.
In any case, there are doubts in the Alliance about the operational readiness of the Turkish army after the purges.
NATO diplomats say that the command structures and operational capabilities have been "weakened".
