Software update for diesel vehicles: What those affected need to know now
How exactly does the software update take place?
Do diesel drivers have to participate?
The most important questions and answers at a glance.
At the diesel summit, BMW, Daimler, Opel and the VW Group offered software updates for a total of around 5.3 million cars.
They are supposed to improve the emission behaviour of cars in emission classes Euro 5 and partly Euro 6.
Euro 4 diesels or worse are exempt.
Anja Smetanin from the ACE Auto Club Europa gives her assessment:
Is the new action mandatory?
No, the negotiated software updates are voluntary.
"The mandatory updates before only apply to those vehicles that have cheating software," says Anja Smetanin.
Their retrofitting has been ordered by the Federal Motor Transport Authority (KBA).
How and when will customers be informed about updates?
The manufacturers have announced a speedy implementation in the next few months, but have not yet given an exact date.
Daimler has announced that it will write to everyone affected.
If an inspection is due anyway, it will be carried out as part of the inspection.
How long is the retrofitting likely to take?
"It's hard to say," says Smetanin.
It depends on the commitment of the manufacturers and on political pressure.
"Because we have seen that the car manufacturers have not yet acted voluntarily when it comes to the environment."
How long should the update take?
The upgrade itself could take only three to four hours in the workshop.
It could be more time-consuming to get an appointment.
What should drivers who do not drive a BMW, Daimler, Opel or VW car do?
The ACE advises them to wait and see.
Smetanin said that foreign manufacturers would probably follow suit.
Is there now a threat of a massive drop in the price of Euro 4 cars?
