Subsidies for village centre III
Anyone who wants to renovate an aging house can soon get support from the state.
Mayor Albert Schindler and three representatives of STEG Stadtentwicklung informed about this in Empfingen on Wednesday.
At the beginning of the information event, Schindler gave a review of what had happened so far.
There have been redevelopment areas in Empfingen since 1991.
At that time, in the redevelopment area I from 1991 to 2004, the state of Baden-Württemberg had taken over two thirds of the funding.
In the redevelopment area II from 2005 to 2016, the subsidy was still 60 per cent.
For Schindler, the previous redevelopments are a "success project" - after all, it is important to promote inner development and not just to develop new building areas.
On 4 April, Schindler received information from the Karlsruhe Regional Council that there will be a redevelopment area III.
The funding amounts to 833,333 euros, of which 500,000 euros come from the state and the rest from the municipality of Empfingen.
How does a redevelopment area come into being?
According to Schindler, we will examine where the "really old" houses are.
It also plays a role whether there is any interest in redevelopment in the planned area.
If necessary, the boundaries of the area could be changed again.
Martin Keller, Gaby Pietzschmann and Sarah Gotzel represented STEG on Wednesday evening.
Keller presented the contents of the federal-state programme "Socially Integrative City", within the framework of which the redevelopments would then be carried out.
The core of the programme is the revitalisation of inner cities, the improvement of living and working conditions and the maintenance and expansion of infrastructure.
The measures would be carried out on a property-by-property basis.
The redevelopment area would then finally be defined as a statute.
Since 1 January 2017, the approval period for the subsidies has been running until 30 April 2026.
Until September of this year, however, the inventory would first be carried out, in the course of which those involved in the redevelopment area would receive a questionnaire to fill out.
In November or December, if possible, the resolution on the statutes should be passed so that the redevelopment work can begin next year.
Pietzschmann then explained that every municipality has to carry out the aforementioned preliminary studies.
It is a matter of assessing the urban deplorable conditions and deciding when and to what extent redevelopment should take place.
A redevelopment note would then be entered in the land register for the respective property.
Pietzschmann promised to come back to Empfingen herself to get an idea of the situation.
Gotzel stressed that an essential factor for the success of the project is the participation of those involved.
Therefore, there will be questionnaires that will be sent to the citizens by post in the coming weeks and can be filled out until after the end of the summer holidays.
The yellow questionnaire is the "building and property questionnaire", which, among other things, deals with the structural condition and redevelopment intentions.
In the grey questionnaire, the "Household and Housing Questionnaire", information can be provided on the size, layout and occupants of a living space.
The blue "business sheet" is only to be filled out if business premises are operated in the building.
However, Gotzel pointed out that a completed questionnaire is not simultaneously an application for funding.
In addition, new construction measures are not eligible for funding.
Schindler also emphasised that the distribution of subsidies works according to the "first come, first served" principle.
It was not possible to "reserve" funding for later.
Finally, photos of the "Ortskern II" project were shown to make the renovation "palatable" to those present.
