"The offer also applies to 35-hour care, when children stay until 2pm."
46 part-time employees will be on kitchen duty from 1 September: they will heat the delivered food, add salad, raw vegetables and fruit, portion the meal individually, serve the food, clear away, wash up and clean the kitchen.
"The employees are permanently assigned to a day-care centre," says Pommeranz.
The size - there are two-group as well as seven-group facilities - determines the number of hours.
"The kitchen assistants are now part of the day-care team," says Pommeranz with satisfaction.
"They are much more involved and it is easier for the day-care centre management to implement educational concepts.
Because that's also what it's about: healthy eating and cooking lessons.
"The children are supposed to help prepare the food".
The direct connection of the kitchen staff to the team makes sense.
For the children, too.
"They have a known person in the day care centre, a person they are familiar with, and not constantly changing people".
This continuity is important for the children.
The cleaning of the day-care centre rooms - until now also the task of the kitchen staff - will in future be done by special cleaning staff.
This variant - the separation of cleaning and kitchen services - has the charm of improving the quality of the kitchen services, but also that it has turned out to be the most economical for the city in a cost comparison between in-house management and outsourcing, according to the press office.
And that is despite the fact that 46 part-time staff will be newly employed.
"But with around 750 people in the education sector, these hours are not that significant," says Sonja Pommeranz.
