Interview: "Domspatzen Report Exonerates Pope's Brother Georg Ratzinger".
The Regensburg Domspatzen report on the abuse cases exonerates Pope-brother Georg Ratzinger.
This is the opinion of author and historian Michael Hesemann.
The final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg Cathedral Boys' Choir continues to cause discussion.
Christian Weisnder, spokesman for the reform movement "We are Church", told the Deutsche Presse-Agentur after publication that he expects an apology from the former Regensburg bishop and current Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller as well as from cathedral conductor Georg Ratzinger, the 93-year-old brother of Pope Emeritus Benedict XVI.
It would greatly serve the reputation of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger expressed their deep regret for their own omissions or their incorrect assessment of the events at the time.
The Vatican newspaper "Osservatore Romano", on the other hand, criticised that "double standards" were applied in the reporting of violence at the Domspatzen.
With regard to the attacks in Regensburg, no one doubted that they were "shameful and disgraceful acts" that had to be punished and prevented in the future; however, the "degree of media manipulation" was striking, said the author Lucetta Scaraffia, historian and member of the Italian National Bioethics Committee.
"The habit of referring to the Catholic Church as the source of all evils is already part of everyday experience and prepares public opinion to consider it normal," Scaraffia writes.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis also said in an interview with Bayerischer Rundfunk: "People like to go after the Church and this is a found food".
She also pointed out that in her youth "beatings were a quite normal pedagogical means" "to deal with naughty children like me".
She said it was unfair to apply today's standards to earlier decades, because the world had changed.
In connection with the reports on the abuse cases, Pope Brother Georg Ratzinger often appeared.
Completely unjustly, says author and historian Michael Hesemann, who wrote the memoir "My Brother the Pope" with Ratzinger (translated into 12 languages).
"I have to come to Georg Ratzinger's defence," says Hesemann, "because none of this had anything to do with him," he assesses the findings of the final report.
What exactly is in the 440-page report presented by Ulrich Weber, the lawyer commissioned by the Regensburg diocese to clarify the matter?
A total of 547 Regensburg Cathedral Priests were victims of assaults between 1945 and the early 1990s "with a high degree of plausibility", 67 Cathedral Priests were sexually abused.
The final report says the following about Georg Ratzinger, who was active in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994: "In summary, it can be stated that in many cases forms of physical and psychological violence were used by Domkapellmeister R..
Especially in cases of high emotionality, the punishment for the pupils could also turn out to be more severe.
Nevertheless, in contrast to numerous other accused, it is noticeable that many victims appreciated R.'s general humanity and therefore in numerous cases even associate positive memories with him despite violence".
In an interview, Hesemann explains why the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg Cathedral Boys' Choir exonerates Georg Ratzinger in his opinion.
Mr Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "Incidents of Violence against Protected Persons at the Regensburg Cathedral Boys' Choir" gives a contradictory picture of Cathedral Choirmaster Georg Ratzinger.
On the one hand, many students emphasise his "humanity".
On the other hand, he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist who often became violent when a Domspatz did not produce a top musical performance.
As his biographer, what do you think of this final report?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble to read the entire 440-page report from cover to cover, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger is mentioned at all.
Only eight pages are devoted to him and he is clearly cleared of any suspicion of complicity or connivance in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The violent excesses at the preschool also occurred outside his sphere of influence.
At best, he can be accused of having learned about it too late or of not having taken the first hints seriously enough.
The Domspatzengymnasium, where he worked, was perceived by practically all those interviewed as - literally - "salvation", "heaven" and a "better world".
Thus, the vast majority of his pupils also give Georg Ratzinger a very excellent report card, describing him as "warm-hearted", "popular", "sincere", "competent" and "understanding", as an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly provided the boys with cakes, biscuits and sweets and was "always surrounded by bunches of children".
Only a minority complains about his perfectionism and his high emotionality, which sometimes led to outbursts of rage.
The fact that he not only banged chairs and threw the bunch of keys on the floor, but also slapped boys in the face and pulled their hair or ears when they were too cheeky, is something he himself admitted years ago, deeply regretted and apologised for.
To his credit, however, it must be said that such methods of education were widespread in the 1960s and 1970s, among parents and teachers alike.
Do you still know such methods of chastisement?
Of course, I think every one of us who was born before 1968.
I too experienced it in a secular school, a state grammar school.
Compared to what this report is actually about, namely the horrific sexual abuse and the violent excesses at the pre-school, these are admittedly trifles.
One wonders whether it is not more to do with his fame and his role as Benedict XVI's brother that many media outlets have pounced on him.
After all, many who never understood the Bavarian Pope are still eagerly working on him.
But the truth is: the report exonerates Georg Ratzinger in every respect!
In connection with the report, there was a lot of media coverage on the subject of abuse at the Regensburg Cathedral Boys' Choir.
Does the final report accuse Georg Ratzinger of any involvement or complicity in sexual abuse?
Michael Hesemann: Quite clearly no.
Not one of the 67 victims of sexual assault claims to have confided in the cathedral conductor.
Not even the parents were privy.
"I never dared to talk to my father or mother about it," one victim testified on behalf of the others, "It was all very embarrassing to me."
The real problem in clearing up sexual abuse was and is that most victims remain silent out of shame.
If they did not even confide in their parents and siblings, then certainly not in a choirmaster, who in a way would have been a colleague of the perpetrators.
How do the Domspatzen pupils assess Ratzinger's role with regard to the abuse cases?
Michael Hesemann: One interviewed pupil put it this way: "With regard to sexual abuse ... I ... no case in which he (Georg Ratzinger) of all people would have had timely knowledge and could have stopped the respective perpetrator.
I think it ... absurd to assume that he, of all people, would have been able to ... boys have opened up more forcefully or more clearly or more readily to him than to their parents, boarding school directors, guidance counsellors, etc.
That one talks to him about sex ... - unthinkable."
Thus the report comes to the very clear conclusion: "The fact that affected pupils and/or their environment confided in him in advance could not be confirmed within the framework of the investigation".
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger is therefore to be absolved of any complicity.
Thus, he cannot be accused of not having prevented it or not having reported it.
Therefore, there is also no reason to associate his good name with these disgusting crimes, as unfortunately happened in some cases.
There was much talk in the media about "excesses of violence" at the Regensburg Cathedral Boys' Choir.
The former cathedral conductor Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report of "looking the other way".
Does he have to live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: That's the big problem, that in the reporting everything was mixed and blended into a huge melange of sexual abuse and excesses of violence and somewhere in the middle, Georg Ratzinger.
But that is precisely the misuse of the report.
There is a clean separation: between the preschool and the Domspatzen grammar school, between sexual abuse and violent excesses and, let's say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the time since 1945, i.e. also from four decades in which Georg Ratzinger was not choirmaster of the Domspatzen.
All the terrible beatings, the cases in which boys were downright bullied and maltreated by sadistic teachers and suffered terribly as a result, all took place at the pre-school in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where truly scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But cathedral conductor Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them, because he only got to see the boys when they were already at the Domspatzengymnasium.
At that school, as most witnesses emphasise, the subject of "pre-school" was taboo.
They were just happy to have escaped it and enjoyed the much better treatment and, for many, even "paradisiacal" conditions.
What was different at the Domspatzengymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but no sadistic violence.
And that also applies to Georg Ratzinger, for whom the report concludes that "many victims appreciated R.'s general humanity and therefore, in numerous cases, even associate positive memories with him despite the violence".
So the most that remains is the accusation of having looked the other way.
But despite all efforts, the report was only able to define two periods in which he was told about the conditions at the preschool.
The first time was in 1970/71, when he was just beginning to establish himself and (according to the witness) did not want to hear anything about what was going on at a school where he did not work and was not responsible, and then again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears to the situation?
Michael Hesemann: No, because as early as 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
In it, he points out to him "that corporal punishment continues to be practised in the pre-school".
Already in view of the danger of negative press publications, he recommended urgent intervention.
This was, of course, at a time when legal clarity existed, when corporal punishment had long since been banned in Bavaria as well.
Before that, they occurred in a legal grey area, as each of us probably remembers.
It was difficult for him to assess where those affected were perhaps exaggerating or dramatising and where the permissible limit had really been crossed.
But you can't say he always looked the other way either.
That is simply not true.
It was not until 1980 that corporal punishment in schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today's educational standards to that time.
How do you see that?
Michael Hesemann: We historians talk about the "pitfall of anachronism", i.e. the danger of evaluating the past according to today's moral standards.
The princess is right about that.
But of course that does not apply to sexual abuse, which was abhorrent at all times, nor to the abominations and violence perpetrated against innocent children's souls in preschool, which goes far beyond what was usual at the time.
It is all terrible and I am glad that it is finally being dealt with.
But at the same time I have to defend Georg Ratzinger, because all this had nothing to do with him.
His means of discipline and punishment, i.e. slapping and pulling hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When corporal punishment was then banned, he also strictly adhered to it.
What image of his time in Regensburg did Georg Ratzinger give in the conversations with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Did the subject of corporal punishment also come up?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, i.e. Pope Benedict XVI, told from his perspective, and the Domspatzen only played a minor role.
Nevertheless, I am by no means concealing the fact that he ran a strict regime there.
But that also has to be said: Without this perfectionism, without the demand for unconditional discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to turn the previously rather nationally known Regensburger Domspatzen into a world-class institution, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition, who went on tour twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
Biscuits and sweets alone do not make great singers out of stubborn boys, and before every success, no matter in what field, there is always discipline, passion and self-conquest.
What kind of person did you experience Georg Ratzinger to be during the discussions on your book?
Michael Hesemann: Through the work on the book and beyond, I really got to know Georg Ratzinger quite well and experienced him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, fundamentally kind, deeply religious and kind-hearted person of whom one cannot imagine that he could harm even a fly.
I regularly hear how many former Domspatzen still keep in regular contact with him, 23 years after his retirement, visit him, read to him - he is almost blind - and treat him like a member of their family.
So those who to this day do not forgive him for once being hard on them are clearly in the minority.
Most of the Domspatzen are grateful to him today for enriching their lives and introducing them to the world of music.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher - a strict father, certainly, that may be - but also a lovable person of respect to whom they still look up to today and whom they virtually revere.
And please, once again very clearly: Everything that he is accused of are educational methods that were the order of the day at that time.
We can be glad that we have long since overcome those times.
But it is highly unfair to make a man a media scapegoat just because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother.
There, the evil intention behind it is all too obvious.
For the report that has just been published exonerates him.
Now decency would dictate that a 93-year-old man who has earned great merits and without whom no one outside Bavaria and perhaps even Germany would know the Regensburg Cathedral Boys' Choir, should finally be left in peace.
